    },
    {
      "id": "jhMCc5hTH7siyZT0qiRA2",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 226.92146283727755,
      "y": -12829.060899611442,
      "width": 562.5914306640625,
      "height": 80,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bAz",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1290520830,
      "version": 269,
      "versionNonce": 1167342590,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765254255873,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "define what makes client unique:\n1. userId: in case of authenticated user. THis is used\n2. IP address: good for public APIs. Found in X-Forwarded-For header. \n3. API key: good for developer apis. Found in X-API-Key header. ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "define what makes client unique:\n1. userId: in case of authenticated user. THis is used\n2. IP address: good for public APIs. Found in X-Forwarded-For header. \n3. API key: good for developer apis. Found in X-API-Key header. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "LQcEeYdBeBaugOkJL9rib",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 56.261390315779295,
      "y": -12688.370278632316,
      "width": 517.887451171875,
      "height": 60,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bB0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1696896190,
      "version": 177,
      "versionNonce": 98875426,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765255948082,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2) System should limit requests on the basis of configurable rules:\n\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2) System should limit requests on the basis of configurable rules:\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "vOVfPEa8gily_BVuGBB1s",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 231.30782783631324,
      "y": -12623.270922086478,
      "width": 769.103515625,
      "height": 700,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bB1",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 723918434,
      "version": 1788,
      "versionNonce": 1420394942,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765255842802,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "There are various algos with diff/ functionalities and rules:\n\n1/ fixed window counter: \n      - check the diagram in blog.\n      - at each time counter is set to zero. \nThe real concern is if multiple requests are made at the boundaries. It creates the issue. \nIn 2 sec 200 requests, if the limit is 100req/minute. The 200 are made at the end of last minute\nand start of new minute.\n\nImplmn: keep a hash map of userId and timestamp. Then keep updating the counter.\n\n2/ Sliding window log.\n\n      - keep a log of all the requests made by the user\n      - then at each request, its timestamp and timestamp-N minutes value is kept.\n    This way count of requests in last N minute is there. \n\n    - The downside is to keep the enteries of limit for each N minute for each client. It \nis lot of memory.\n\n3/ sliding window counter:\n    - clever approach of approximation\n    - 30% into current minute , 70% from last is taken. The count is found using both \n    if it is less than threshold.\n\n4/ token bucket:\n    1. store the bucket size and refill rate for each client. Let's say 100 tokens is the capacity\nwith 10 tokens/minute are updated.\n    2. If tokens>0, then request is passed.\n    3. check the redis transaction part, where read should be part of update\nin the blog. \n   4. redis works perfectly for speed, automatic cleanup, high available and atomic operations.\n\n\n   ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "There are various algos with diff/ functionalities and rules:\n\n1/ fixed window counter: \n      - check the diagram in blog.\n      - at each time counter is set to zero. \nThe real concern is if multiple requests are made at the boundaries. It creates the issue. \nIn 2 sec 200 requests, if the limit is 100req/minute. The 200 are made at the end of last minute\nand start of new minute.\n\nImplmn: keep a hash map of userId and timestamp. Then keep updating the counter.\n\n2/ Sliding window log.\n\n      - keep a log of all the requests made by the user\n      - then at each request, its timestamp and timestamp-N minutes value is kept.\n    This way count of requests in last N minute is there. \n\n    - The downside is to keep the enteries of limit for each N minute for each client. It \nis lot of memory.\n\n3/ sliding window counter:\n    - clever approach of approximation\n    - 30% into current minute , 70% from last is taken. The count is found using both \n    if it is less than threshold.\n\n4/ token bucket:\n    1. store the bucket size and refill rate for each client. Let's say 100 tokens is the capacity\nwith 10 tokens/minute are updated.\n    2. If tokens>0, then request is passed.\n    3. check the redis transaction part, where read should be part of update\nin the blog. \n   4. redis works perfectly for speed, automatic cleanup, high available and atomic operations.\n\n\n   ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "TEVORellWBhMNQCgzM0uc",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 60.25276717327941,
      "y": -11921.90925097633,
      "width": 864.895263671875,
      "height": 360,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bB3",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 127836322,
      "version": 1036,
      "versionNonce": 238308642,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765256324515,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3) requests failed, then reject with HTTP 429 status code and helpful headers.\n\n Multiple headers for giving info to user to retry. The one desing option is to queue requests\nand handle when limit resets.\nIssue is memory , COGS on the service side. Then user might think they are waiting, they might retry\nand increase load on our service. best is to fail fast. \nCheck the section for diff/ headers in the blog.\n\n\nDeep Dives:\n\n1. Handle scale of 1M requests/second:\n       One single redis instance can handle scale of 100-200k requests per minute. \n     In Rate limiter need is read, update as a single atomic operation for each requests. \n\n   Taking an approximation of 100k requests handled by one redis instance, then 10 such instance are needed. \n\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3) requests failed, then reject with HTTP 429 status code and helpful headers.\n\n Multiple headers for giving info to user to retry. The one desing option is to queue requests\nand handle when limit resets.\nIssue is memory , COGS on the service side. Then user might think they are waiting, they might retry\nand increase load on our service. best is to fail fast. \nCheck the section for diff/ headers in the blog.\n\n\nDeep Dives:\n\n1. Handle scale of 1M requests/second:\n       One single redis instance can handle scale of 100-200k requests per minute. \n     In Rate limiter need is read, update as a single atomic operation for each requests. \n\n   Taking an approximation of 100k requests handled by one redis instance, then 10 such instance are needed. \n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
