      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765256561363,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. consistent hashing might be used for sharding.\n2. In real this is handled by redis cluster, not by instance. ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. consistent hashing might be used for sharding.\n2. In real this is handled by redis cluster, not by instance. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "CvWoJhGhUf618WHuCWDNp",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 23.90360516100958,
      "y": -11195.905433205933,
      "width": 718.0474243164062,
      "height": 740,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bBT",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 250474814,
      "version": 2018,
      "versionNonce": 1068367251,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765257921098,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2/ ensure availability and fault tolerance\n\n   1. Keep the redis master-slave replica. \n   2. Then also it fails then chose between fail open vs fail close. both are fine,\n   depending on the use case. \n   3. cehck the diagram in the blog. \n   4. monitoring and alerting will be in place for this system which is \n   one of the first requirement.\n\n3/ How do we minimize latency overhead.\n     1. two things, first is connection pooling. Saves the back and forth of \n    handshakes in tcp connection.\n    2. Keep the servers close to the user. It includes api gateway, rate limiter\n  and service in the same region.\n    3. other optmzn are not impt, can be checked in the highlighted section. local caching\nand batching of lua scripts for atomic read-updates.\n\n\n4/ handle hot keys:\n\n    few strategies:\n   1. ask clients to have some kind of rate limiting on their side. \n   2. allow clients to batch mulitple operations in single requests.\n   3. premium users have some diff/ infra.\n\nIn case of users are not legitimate block them and keep them in one of the redis\nshard and not allow any of their request.  \n\n5/ handle dynamic rule configuration:\n\n    1. pull based: keep config like clienttype, limit in the db, then at each fixed interval\n  that data can be pulled. Issue is there is time gap in bwn pulling data and update\n   2. push based: use of zookeeper/etcd as central config store where \n  values are updated. The events are automatically sent to the redis. Handle \nthe scenarios if some instance did not pick the event. This approach is faster and complex.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2/ ensure availability and fault tolerance\n\n   1. Keep the redis master-slave replica. \n   2. Then also it fails then chose between fail open vs fail close. both are fine,\n   depending on the use case. \n   3. cehck the diagram in the blog. \n   4. monitoring and alerting will be in place for this system which is \n   one of the first requirement.\n\n3/ How do we minimize latency overhead.\n     1. two things, first is connection pooling. Saves the back and forth of \n    handshakes in tcp connection.\n    2. Keep the servers close to the user. It includes api gateway, rate limiter\n  and service in the same region.\n    3. other optmzn are not impt, can be checked in the highlighted section. local caching\nand batching of lua scripts for atomic read-updates.\n\n\n4/ handle hot keys:\n\n    few strategies:\n   1. ask clients to have some kind of rate limiting on their side. \n   2. allow clients to batch mulitple operations in single requests.\n   3. premium users have some diff/ infra.\n\nIn case of users are not legitimate block them and keep them in one of the redis\nshard and not allow any of their request.  \n\n5/ handle dynamic rule configuration:\n\n    1. pull based: keep config like clienttype, limit in the db, then at each fixed interval\n  that data can be pulled. Issue is there is time gap in bwn pulling data and update\n   2. push based: use of zookeeper/etcd as central config store where \n  values are updated. The events are automatically sent to the redis. Handle \nthe scenarios if some instance did not pick the event. This approach is faster and complex.\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
