    },
    {
      "id": "KulYppKAtbgz0_MVnkOem",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2375.6274465473484,
      "y": -4816.04056167322,
      "width": 902.739501953125,
      "height": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bBs",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1540063422,
      "version": 255,
      "versionNonce": 98973758,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770473590623,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When the client fails:\nreturns the 429 status code with calls got exceeded. Ensure that the some other headers \ncontaining info like how many requests have been pending, reset time will also help.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When the client fails:\nreturns the 429 status code with calls got exceeded. Ensure that the some other headers \ncontaining info like how many requests have been pending, reset time will also help.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "wYDcuUmwB6dqWNnjg7eQQ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2524.7934612310346,
      "y": -4617.103243779992,
      "width": 1039.29931640625,
      "height": 1400,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bBt",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1486462434,
      "version": 3162,
      "versionNonce": 1306270242,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770522567342,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Potential deep dives:\n\n1. scaling to 1M req/second.\n  one redis instance will be able to handle complex query patterns upto 100k req/sec. We need \n10 instances that way. \nThe solution is to shard the data on the basis of different client either be ip address, client id or api \nkey. The consistent hashing is used here. \nIdeally the redis cluster handles it internally we need not to take care of it. \n\n\n2. high availability and fault tolerance\nThere are two ways to handle this failure one is fail closed and another is fail open.\n  Fail closed: is not allowing any traffic to pass through due to rate limiter failure of redis\n  fail open: open all the traffic to pass through. The main issue is that if redis did go down due \nto high traffic it will make my whole service down now.\n\nSocial media do fail closed so that the big traffic does not make my platform down. \nThe better solution in any case is to have proper alerting and monitoring in place which includes\ncpu usage, memory consumption and network connectivity across shards.\nAsync replica of redis will help in failover scenarios. The replica will come up if master goes down.\n\n\n3. latency overhead reduction:\nthe main solution is connection pooling. This helps in reducing the back and forth of setting\nup the network with redis connection. \nThe second solution is regional deployment of api gateways where user is located.\n\n4. hot keys:\nthere can be two scenarios this can happen one is legitimate users and another is malicious users.\nBoth should be handled in diff/ ways\n\n  - legitimate users: client side rate limiting can be asked, request queuing and batching, keep some premium\ntier through some custom infra to handle their load\n  - malicious users - keep some automatic blocking for them use the blocking list of redis to block\nthis kind of traffic in redis. For DDoS protection can use some cloudflare tech\n\n5. handle dynamic rule configuration\n\nThere are two ways to go with one is using the polling appraoch, this will fail due to issue in \nhigh cpu usage and latency of getting the rule updates once changes has been made. In worst case\nscenarios this can create issues\n\nThe second solution is using zookeeper which is meant for distributed configuration management with\nreal time notifications.\n\nClient -> api gateway -> server\n             |\n            zookeeper which sends events to api gateway which in turn is connected to redis \nclusters in order to serve the rate limiting thing.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Potential deep dives:\n\n1. scaling to 1M req/second.\n  one redis instance will be able to handle complex query patterns upto 100k req/sec. We need \n10 instances that way. \nThe solution is to shard the data on the basis of different client either be ip address, client id or api \nkey. The consistent hashing is used here. \nIdeally the redis cluster handles it internally we need not to take care of it. \n\n\n2. high availability and fault tolerance\nThere are two ways to handle this failure one is fail closed and another is fail open.\n  Fail closed: is not allowing any traffic to pass through due to rate limiter failure of redis\n  fail open: open all the traffic to pass through. The main issue is that if redis did go down due \nto high traffic it will make my whole service down now.\n\nSocial media do fail closed so that the big traffic does not make my platform down. \nThe better solution in any case is to have proper alerting and monitoring in place which includes\ncpu usage, memory consumption and network connectivity across shards.\nAsync replica of redis will help in failover scenarios. The replica will come up if master goes down.\n\n\n3. latency overhead reduction:\nthe main solution is connection pooling. This helps in reducing the back and forth of setting\nup the network with redis connection. \nThe second solution is regional deployment of api gateways where user is located.\n\n4. hot keys:\nthere can be two scenarios this can happen one is legitimate users and another is malicious users.\nBoth should be handled in diff/ ways\n\n  - legitimate users: client side rate limiting can be asked, request queuing and batching, keep some premium\ntier through some custom infra to handle their load\n  - malicious users - keep some automatic blocking for them use the blocking list of redis to block\nthis kind of traffic in redis. For DDoS protection can use some cloudflare tech\n\n5. handle dynamic rule configuration\n\nThere are two ways to go with one is using the polling appraoch, this will fail due to issue in \nhigh cpu usage and latency of getting the rule updates once changes has been made. In worst case\nscenarios this can create issues\n\nThe second solution is using zookeeper which is meant for distributed configuration management with\nreal time notifications.\n\nClient -> api gateway -> server\n             |\n            zookeeper which sends events to api gateway which in turn is connected to redis \nclusters in order to serve the rate limiting thing.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
  ],
